Protocols/RBKLivenessCameraDelegate.html.name: RBKLivenessCameraDelegate
Protocols/RBKLivenessCameraDelegate.html.abstract: RBKLivenessCameraDelegate: A protocol that outlines the essential methods for receiving notifications from a liveness detection camera system within an iOS application. This delegate is crucial for integrating face detection functionalities with the UI and other components of the app, facilitating real-time interactions based on camera events. Implementers of this protocol can manage and respond to various camera-related events, such as face capture, face detection, and user movement.

Enums/RBKLivenessAction.html.name: RBKLivenessAction
Enums/RBKLivenessAction.html.abstract: RBKLivenessAction: An enumeration that defines specific actions related to liveness detection within an iOS application using face recognition technology. Each case of this enumeration represents a different physical action that a user might be required to perform in front of the camera to verify their presence and identity. This enum is integral to the functioning of systems that require enhanced security measures through biometric verification methods.

Classes/RBKCameraController.html.name: RBKCameraController
Classes/RBKCameraController.html.abstract: RBKCameraController: A UIViewController subclass specifically designed to handle the complexities of managing camera functionalities within an iOS application. This class integrates directly with the AVFoundation framework to manage an AVCaptureSession for capturing video and photo content. It provides a robust infrastructure for configuring, displaying, and controlling the camera capture session.

Classes/RBKLivenessViewController.html.name: RBKLivenessViewController
Classes/RBKLivenessViewController.html.abstract: RBKLivenessViewController: A UIViewController subclass that orchestrates the user interface and interaction flows for liveness detection in an iOS application. This class integrates various components including a camera controller, UI elements like labels and activity indicators, and business logic through an associated interactor. It manages the presentation of camera feeds, user prompts (e.g., “Turn your head to the left”), and feedback based on liveness detection results.
